** The Power of Perception and Critical Imagination: Alfred Kazin on Embra=
cing Contradiction and How the Sacredness of Human Attention Shapes Our Re=
ality (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/20/alfred-kazin-journals-perc=
eption-contradiction/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/030014203X/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ded7=
ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CReality is what we take to be true=2C=E2=80=9D pioneering physici=
st David Bohm asserted in 1977 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/09/22/t=
he-quantum-and-the-lotus-riccard-david-bohm-reality/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&m=
c_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . =E2=80=9CWhat we take to be true is what we believe.=
 What we believe is based upon our perceptions. What we perceive depends o=
n what we look for. What we look for depends on what we think. What we thi=
nk depends on what we perceive. What we perceive determines what we believ=
e. What we believe determines what we take to be true. What we take to be=
 true is our reality.=E2=80=9D

How our perception shapes our experience of reality=2C and how that can be=
 a source of power=2C is what the great Jewish-American writer and literar=
y critic Alfred Kazin (June 5=2C 1915=E2=80=93June 5=2C 1998) explored twe=
nty years earlier in a series of entires from Alfred Kazin=E2=80=99s Journ=
als (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/030014203X/braipick-20?mc_cid=
=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org=
/title/alfred-kazins-journals/oclc/670481407&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_ci=
d=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 an immensely rewarding trov=
e of wisdom in the tradition of the journals of Thoreau (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2015/02/10/thoreau-hard-work-efficiency/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Andr=C3=A9 Gide (https://www.brainpickings.org/201=
5/03/13/andre-gide-journals-sincerity/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) =2C Anne Truitt (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/01/anne-truitt=
-turn-regret-mourning-love/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C an=
d Susan Sontag (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/01/05/susan-sontag-rebo=
rn-rereading/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C which endure as=
 a sort of secular scripture and to which I return for comfort=2C consolat=
ion=2C and
emboldenment in trying times.

Radiating from Kazin=E2=80=99s unrelenting introspection is uncommon insig=
ht into the human spirit and a willingness to contact=2C even to embrace=
=2C all of its dimensions =E2=80=94 the awe and the anguish=2C the exultan=
t and the exasperating=2C all of it riding acrest an ebbing undercurrent o=
f imperfection.

Alfred Kazin=2C 1946 (Photograph: Henri Cartier-Bresson/Magnum)

Three days before his forty-second birthday=2C Kazin writes:

Trust to the contradictions and see them all. Never annul one force to giv=
e supremacy to another. The contradiction itself is the reality in all its=
 manifoldness. Man from his vantage point can see reality only in contradi=
ctions. And the more faithful he is to his perception of the contradiction=
=2C the more he is open to what there is for him to know. =E2=80=9CHarmony=
=E2=80=9D as an absolute good is for the gods=2C not for man.

Cautioning against chasing the myth of harmony =E2=80=94 a myth advanced=
=2C perhaps most famously=2C by Emerson and woven into the fabric of moder=
n culture in tyrannical ideals like =E2=80=9Cwork/life balance=E2=80=9D (h=
ttps://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/11/david-whyte-three-marriages-work-l=
ife/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 Kazin writes:

A thinker (like [Ralph Waldo Emerson]) misleads us as soon as he promotes=
 harmony as the exclusive goal=2C and especially misleads us when he preac=
hes harmony as a method. Man=E2=80=99s life is full of contradiction and h=
e must be; we see through a glass darkly =E2=80=94 we want more than we ca=
n have; we see more than we can understand. But a contradiction that is fa=
ced leads to true knowledge=E2=80=A6 Contradictions are on the surface=2C=
 the symbols of deeper and more fertile forces that can unleash the most m=
arvelous energy when they are embraced. Never try to achieve =E2=80=9Corde=
r=2C=E2=80=9D sacrifice symmetry =E2=80=94 seek to relate all these antago=
nistic forces=2C not to let the elimination of one to the other. The idea=
 of =E2=80=9CGod=E2=80=9D as perfect order is perilous to man as an ideal=
=2C for us to follow=E2=80=A6

=E2=80=9CUnder the Third Avenue El=E2=80=9D by Weegee=2C 1943-1945 (Intern=
ational Center of Photography)

The same perilous resistance to contradiction=2C Kazin observes in another=
 entry penned the following month=2C is what undergirds our cult of self-i=
mprovement. Half a century before the heyday of self-help books and websit=
es=2C which commodify human life as a problem to be solved rather than a g=
lorious mystery to be savored=2C he writes:

The other day =E2=80=A6 I suddenly realized=2C with a shudder almost =E2=
=80=A6 how easy it is to fall into the other-imposed trap of trying endles=
sly to correct and reform oneself=2C in accordance with this and that=2C o=
ne=E2=80=99s idea of the right person to be=2C when all the time=2C one is=
 not merely =E2=80=9Cstuck=E2=80=9D with oneself=2C as one is rightly enou=
gh=2C but one suffers from constrictedness=2C from reaction=2C from the mi=
llion-and-one reasons=2C so boringly personified around one in one=E2=80=
=99s contemporaries and half-friends and stupid=2C genteel colleagues=2C w=
ho are always telling us over again that man is bad and sinful!

Kazin=E2=80=99s journal is strewn with this restless search for self-gener=
ated sacredness =E2=80=94 for a source of goodness and meaning not imposed=
 from without=2C be it by spiritual mythology or by secular society=2C but=
 synthesized from within. It comes most acutely alive in an entry penned e=
arlier that year=2C in which Kazin reflects on Auden=E2=80=99s notion of=
 =E2=80=9Csacred objects=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 catalysts for awe=2C which ins=
pire the basic impulse to make art =E2=80=94 and writes:

Without worship=2C without respect=2C without wonder=2C without the great=
 work with which our wonder and awe plunge us=2C what is there =E2=80=94 w=
hat?

But the =E2=80=9Cmodern=E2=80=9D epoch is precisely that in which each of=
 us must discover our gods for ourselves. This is why so much in our langu=
age reverts to the idea of a fall=2C a descent. As Satan fell=2C to rise a=
gain as a prince of life=2C so we fall into this maelstrom=2C this madness=
 =E2=80=94 this world in which nothing any longer is given to us =E2=80=94=
 to discover=2C in pain and awe=2C our own sacred objects.

Like those of us who choose to live with what philosopher Erich Fromm term=
ed rational faith in the human spirit (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/=
04/04/erich-fromm-anatomy-of-human-destructiveness/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc=
_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Kazin was a resolute humanist who knew that beauty a=
nd goodness don=E2=80=99t merely befall us but come into being in the very=
 act of our looking for them =E2=80=94 nowhere more so than when it comes=
 to our fellow human beings. In a diary entry from August of 1957=2C he co=
ntemplates an image by the legendary New York street photographer Weegee=
 =E2=80=94 who was doing half a century ago what Humans of New York=E2=80=
=98s Brandon Stanton (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/15/humans-of-n=
ew-york-brandon-stanton-design-matters-interview/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) is doing now =E2=80=94 and writes:

It is so important to keep the eye glued to the reality of the actual holi=
ness! When I saw those Times Square faces in Weegee=E2=80=99s pictures yes=
terday=2C the women with that horrible fat and those indriven eyeglasses=
=2C I suddenly saw the beauty of the actual living hour in the human strug=
gle of those faces =E2=80=94 and of those faces alone. Somehow only the hu=
man being tells the story=2C only the human breath counts. The honor only=
 the human heart ever knows=E2=80=A6 And even when the lonely transcendent=
al heart stands poised upon an empty rock looking out to sea=2C it is this=
 man=2C this mind=2C that makes the scene =E2=80=94 not the rock and the s=
ea=2C but the human eye that alone has united them. The human mind alone m=
akes the radius to every point on the circumference=2C the great wheel on=
 which we ride. The human eye alone unites the world =E2=80=94 by percepti=
on=E2=80=A6

Several weeks later=2C Kazin revisits the reality-shaping power of percept=
ion and suggests that how we choose to perceive the world is a centerpiece=
 of our critical faculty; that a benevolent curiosity about our fellow hum=
ans is how we hold on to our own humanity. In an entry from September 28 o=
f 1957=2C which resounds with remarkable timeliness amid our present cultu=
ral and political climate=2C he writes:

The critical imagination is distinguished by its voracious curiosity.

[=E2=80=A6]

This retreat from curiosity=2C from interest in the outside would as conti=
nuously interesting=2C comes from our lack of politics=2C our lack of fait=
h in the possibility of change.

That possibility=2C Kazin argues=2C must =E2=80=9Cstart from the observer=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 from the idea that one cannot =E2=80=9Cpretend [to be=
] a disembodied intelligence coolly reading the times.=E2=80=9D Echoing Su=
san Sontag=E2=80=99s timeless assertion that in order to be a good writer=
 and a moral human being one must =E2=80=9Cpay attention to the world=2C=
=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/30/susan-sontag-writing-s=
torytelling-at-the-same-time/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Kazi=
n considers yet another contradiction:

The problem=2C of course=2C is not to go too far the other way into introv=
ersion. And probably the safest path is always to think of the observer as=
 a developing=2C living=2C growing agent=2C so that the self that is engag=
ed in thinking out the world will feel itself growing only as the thoughts=
 grow.

But meanwhile=2C the day=2C the living day=2C the actual moment=2C the pan=
g of real life=2C =E2=80=94 to be faithful to this=2C one must always pay=
 attention=2C one must never dismiss anything a priority as too trivial. N=
othing is too trivial=2C for what the writer may make of it.

=E2=80=9CSummer on the Lower East Side=E2=80=9D by Weegee=2C 1937 (Interna=
tional Center of Photography)

Exactly two months later=2C he records his joyful surrender to this living=
=2C breathing world in an exultant counterpoint to our urban loneliness (h=
ttps://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/11/the-lonely-city-olivia-laing/?mc_c=
id=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) :

How alive the city is=2C how alive=2C how alive=2C how alive. Each of thos=
e windows has someone behind it=2C each of these streets is a current unde=
r my feet. A network of people=2C a living field =E2=80=94 each grass a so=
ul=2C each grass alive. So let us give thanks after all=2C and be glad=2C=
 and rejoice. To be in life with so many people!

Alfred Kazin=E2=80=99s Journals (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/03=
0014203X/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) is a tremendo=
usly vitalizing read in its six-decade totality. Complement it with Kazin=
 on loneliness=2C the immigrant experience=2C and how reading liberates us=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/05/alfred-kazin-walker-in-the-city=
-love/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Emerson on=
 how to live with maximum aliveness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/05=
/25/emerson-essays-lectures-experience/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNI=
QID]) .
