** How Astronomer Jocelyn Bell Burnell Shaped Our Understanding of the Uni=
verse by Discovering Pulsars=2C Only to Be Excluded from the Nobel Prize (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/15/jocelyn-bell-burnell-pulsar-nobel=
/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0307958191/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ded7=
ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

In July of 1967=2C the month of her twenty-fourth birthday=2C Northern Iri=
sh astrophysicist Jocelyn Bell Burnell (b. July 15=2C 1943) discovered the=
 first pulsar. This was landmark evidence that neutron stars =E2=80=94 the=
 collapsed core left behind by the final explosion of a dying star=2C firs=
t proposed a year after the discovery of the neutron in 1933 =E2=80=94 wer=
e real. But the most significant implication of the discovery was that if=
 neutron stars could result from stellar death=2C so could black holes=2C=
 which even Einstein considered a neat but limited=2C purely mathematical=
=2C and possibly unprovable theoretical construct.

Pulsars =E2=80=94 enormous=2C rapidly spinning=2C extremely dense spheres=
 of nuclear matter magnetized with a strength exceeding Earth=E2=80=99s ma=
gnetic fields by an order of millions=2C even thousands of trillions =E2=
=80=94 thus shaped our present understanding of the universe. Bell Burnell=
 discovered the first four.

Jocelyn Bell Burnell=2C 1960s

The groundbreaking paper announcing the discovery was published four month=
s later=2C listing Bell Burnell=E2=80=99s name second and Antony Hewish=2C=
 her thesis supervisor=2C first.

On October 15=2C 1974=2C the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Hewish=
 and his English colleague Martin Ryle for their work in radioastronomy. T=
he Swedish Academy cited Hewish=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cdecisive role in the di=
scovery of pulsars=E2=80=9D in the official announcement.

Bell Burnell was excluded from the prize.

In a 1977 speech (http://ircamera.as.arizona.edu/NatSci102/NatSci102/image=
s/extlttlgrnmn.htm?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Bell Burnel=
l insisted on not feeling slighted by the Nobel committee=2C citing the di=
fficulty of resolving =E2=80=9Cdemarcation disputes between supervisor and=
 student=E2=80=9D and the belief that =E2=80=9Cit would demean Nobel Prize=
s if they were awarded to research students.=E2=80=9D But it is hard to re=
ad such sentiments without wondering whether there might be a kind of Stoc=
kholm Syndrome of the disenfranchised at work =E2=80=94 after all=2C those=
 systematically marginalized and discriminated against by any power struct=
ure have no choice but to rationalize injustice as a coping mechanism if t=
hey are to continue operating within that ecosystem without being broken b=
y its biases.

Cosmologist Janna Levin explores Bell Burnell=E2=80=99s pioneering contrib=
ution to science=2C its far-reaching implications=2C and the complexities=
 surrounding the Nobel controversy in a portion of Black Hole Blues and Ot=
her Songs from Outer Space (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0307958=
191/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (h=
ttp://www.worldcat.org/title/black-hole-blues-and-other-songs-from-outer-s=
pace/oclc/932115990&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[=
