Levin writes:

There is nothing like plain observation to finally resolve a theoretical s=
tandoff. Jocelyn Bell Burnell found evidence of a neutron star. Added to t=
he sheer intrinsic fascination of that discovery was the promise of even m=
ore=2C the promise of black holes. (An illustrious colleague is reported t=
o have intercepted her at a meeting to declare=2C =E2=80=9CMiss Bell=2C yo=
u have made the greatest astronomical discovery of the twentieth century.=
=E2=80=9D)

With her characteristic subtlety and sensitivity to nuance=2C Levin shares=
 in the skepticism about such wholesale acquittal of prejudice:

Hewish need not defend his credibility as a Nobel laureate. As the advisor=
 he set his student to the task =E2=80=94 even if the task was to look for=
 quasars. Harder to comprehend is the omission of Jocelyn Bell Burnell fro=
m the list of recipients. I ask her if she thought her former advisor shou=
ld have done something more=2C and she says with no resentment=2C =E2=80=
=9CIf you get a prize=2C it=E2=80=99s not your job to explain why you got=
 the prize.=E2=80=9D She also adds that the slight has worked out for her=
 quite well. She continues to get seemingly every other prize=2C medal=2C=
 honor=2C and accolade ever invented. Fair compensation she seems to imply=
=2E Dame (Susan) Jocelyn Bell Burnell: dame commander of the Most Excellent=
 Order of the British Empire=2C fellow of the Royal Society=2C president o=
f the Royal Society of Edinburgh=2C fellow of the Royal Astronomical Socie=
ty=2C many distinguished medals=2C dozens of honorary doctorates etc.=2C e=
tc.=2C etc.

The specter of bias had haunted Bell Burnell since the dawn of her career.=
 According to Ron Drever =E2=80=94 the cantankerous Scottish genius compri=
sing one third of the famed LIGO Troika (http://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/24=
/books/review/maria-popova-reviews-janna-levins-black-hole-blues.html?_r=
=3D0&mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C who served as young Jocel=
yn=E2=80=99s undergraduate advisor in Glasgow =E2=80=94 she was denied emp=
loyment at England=E2=80=99s foremost radio astronomy center in the mid-19=
60s on account of her gender. Levin follows the thread:

[Drever] relays=2C =E2=80=9CThey wouldn=E2=80=99t take her on=2C and the=
 story was that it was because she was a woman. But that=E2=80=99s not off=
icial=2C you see. So she was very disappointed.=E2=80=9D He adds=2C hoping=
 the absurdity was obvious=2C =E2=80=9CHer second best was to go to Cambri=
dge. You see?=E2=80=9D He considered this a very fortuitous and happy turn=
=2E He laughs. =E2=80=9CSo she went to Cambridge and discovered pulsars. You=
 see?=E2=80=9D

Later in her career=2C Jocelyn Bell Burnell moved into X-ray astronomy to=
 work on the team that built the British-American Ariel 5 X-ray astronomy=
 satellite. On October 10=2C 1974=2C early in the morning=2C Ariel launche=
d successfully=2C and at noon she heard the announcement of the Nobel Priz=
e for the discovery of pulsars. There were two aspects of the announcement=
 that were of particular significance to her. For one=2C the Nobel committ=
ee had finally acknowledged astrophysics as a subfield worthy of the Nobel=
 Prize in Physics. In the 1920s Edwin Hubble had campaigned for such a shi=
ft unsuccessfully. For another=2C she was not among the recipients.

To grasp the scope of this systemic predicament: Crowning the hierarchy of=
 British academia are the so-called =E2=80=9Cfull professors=2C=E2=80=9D d=
istinguished from the vast court of mere doctors. Even at the height of he=
r career=2C Bell Burnell was one of only two women among the 150 such full=
 professors in Britain.

PSR 1919 (after Jocelyn Bell Burnell) from Your Body is a Space That Sees=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/07/your-body-is-a-space-that-sees-=
lia-halloran/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C artist Lia Hallo=
