And yet in the midst of this maelstrom of politics and esteemed extrinsic=
 validation is the perennial heart of science itself=2C that utmost intrin=
sic reward of curiosity =E2=80=94 the sublime exhilaration of discovery (h=
ttps://www.brainpickings.org/2016/02/10/alan-lightman-a-sense-of-the-myste=
rious-1/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Levin telescopes to tha=
t luminous moment=2C which changed Bell Burnell=E2=80=99s life and changed=
 our basic understanding of the cosmos:

As a twenty-four-year-old graduate student at Cambridge=2C [Bell Burnell]=
 and her advisor=2C Antony Hewish=2C were looking for quasars=2C bright ra=
dio sources that looked as small as stars. At the time that she was string=
ing radio antennae in the field=2C quasars were still called quasi-stellar=
 radio objects and the sources were a mystery. The radio antennae worked w=
ell at finding quasars=2C poorly at resolving their sizes=2C and brilliant=
ly at changing the course of astrophysics. Among the quasars detected were=
 many glitches and peculiarities recorded on the reams of chart paper=2C q=
uantified by the length of paper in feet. She examined hundreds (thousands=
?) of feet of paper meticulously. Most of the anomalies were attributable=
 to human-made sources or some form of detector interference. But one funn=
y signal persisted. She became convinced that the source was astronomical=
 in origin. She said the realization that she had seen something truly imp=
ortant came gradually. As is often reported=2C
the regularity of the signal earned the sources the internal nickname of L=
GM=2C for =E2=80=9Clittle green men.=E2=80=9D It turns out that there are=
 even more precise clocks than those manufactured by the civilizations of=
 little intelligent green men. And those would be pulsars.

[=E2=80=A6]

When Jocelyn Bell Burnell discovered the first pulsar in 1967=2C all she c=
ould deduce for certain was that there was a very regular series of pulses=
=2C a little over a second apart=2C and that they were coming from the sky=
=2E

When the second one appeared in the data=2C =E2=80=9Cthat was the sweet mo=
ment=2C=E2=80=9D she says. That=E2=80=99s when the oddity began to take on=
 the features of a discovery. =E2=80=9COnce I=E2=80=99d seen one scruffy s=
ignal=2C I was open to seeing more.=E2=80=9D She found the first four puls=
ars ever discovered by human beings.

A year later a pulsar was discovered in the center of the Crab Nebula=2C a=
 luminous remnant ejected during a supernova explosion. The Crab Nebula wa=
s seen from Earth and noted in historical records as an astronomical event=
 in 1054 AD. The implication: Neutron stars are the collapsed core that re=
mains after a dying star explodes. We now extrapolate that there are hundr=
eds of millions of neutron stars in our galaxy=2C and hundreds of thousand=
s of these are pulsars.

Composite X-ray and optical Hubble image of the Crab Nebula depicting sync=
hrotron emission in the surrounding pulsar wind nebula=2C powered by magne=
tic fields and particles from the central pulsar

