** The Effortless Effort of Creativity: Jane Hirshfield on Storytelling=2C=
 the Art of Concentration=2C and Difficulty as a Consecrating Force of Cre=
ative Attention (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/21/jane-hirshfield-=
concentration/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0060929480/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ded7=
ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CThe poets (by which I mean all artists) are finally the only peop=
le who know the truth about us=2C=E2=80=9D James Baldwin wrote in lamentin=
g the artist=E2=80=99s struggle (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/13/=
james-baldwin-the-artists-struggle-for-integrity/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) at a time =E2=80=9Cwhen something awful is happening to a=
 civilization=2C when it ceases to produce poets=2C and=2C what is even mo=
re crucial=2C when it ceases in any way whatever to believe in the report=
 that only the poets can make.=E2=80=9D We no longer have Baldwin to awake=
n us to the gravest perils of our own era =E2=80=94 one in which the poeti=
c spirit isn=E2=80=99t merely neglected but is being forced to surrender a=
t gunpoint. To produce poets=2C in this largest Baldwinian sense of creati=
ve seers of human truth=2C seems to be among the most urgent tasks of our=
 time.

The mastery of that task is what the poet Jane Hirshfield (https://www.bra=
inpickings.org/2016/07/01/anne-truitt-turn-regret-mourning-love/?mc_cid=3D=
ed7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]#hirshfield) examines in her 1997 essay colle=
ction Nine Gates: Entering the Mind of Poetry (http://www.amazon.com/exec/=
obidos/ASIN/0060929480/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/nine-gates-entering-the-mi=
nd-of-poetry-essays/oclc/36510536&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71=
960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ).

Defining poetry as =E2=80=9Cthe clarification and magnification of being=
=2C=E2=80=9D she writes: =E2=80=9CHere=2C as elsewhere in life=2C attentiv=
eness only deepens what it regards.=E2=80=9D In the superb opening essay=
=2C titled =E2=80=9CPoetry and the Mind of Concentration=2C=E2=80=9D Hirsh=
field examines the nature of this clarified=2C magnified deepening of bein=
g =E2=80=94 concentration as consecration =E2=80=94 by probing its six mai=
n components: music=2C rhetoric=2C image=2C emotion=2C story=2C and voice.=
 Although focused on the reading and writing of poetry=2C her insight ripp=
les outward in widening circles (as Rilke might way) to encompass every ki=
nd of writing=2C all art=2C and even the art of living itself.

Jane Hirshfield (Photograph: Nick Rozsa)

Hirshfield writes:

Every good poem begins in language awake to its own connections =E2=80=94=
 language that hears itself and what is around it=2C sees itself and what=
 is around it=2C looks back at those who look into its gaze and knows more=
 perhaps even than we do about who are=2C what we are. It begins=2C that i=
s=2C in the mind and body of concentration.

By concentration=2C I mean a particular state of awareness: penetrating=2C=
 unified=2C and focused=2C yet also permeable and open. This quality of co=
nsciousness=2C though not easily put into words=2C is instantly recognizab=
le. Aldous Huxley described it as the moment the doors or perception open;=
 James Joyce called in epiphany. The experience of concentration may be qu=
ietly physical=E2=80=94a simple=2C unexpected sense of deep accord between=
 yourself and everything. It may come as the harvest of long looking and l=
eave us=2C as it did Wordsworth=2C a mind thought =E2=80=9Ctoo deep for te=
ars.=E2=80=9D Within action=2C it is felt as a grace state: time slows and=
 extends=2C and a person=E2=80=99s every movement and decision seem to par=
take of perfection. Concentration can also be place into things =E2=80=94=
 it radiates undimmed from Vermeer=E2=80=99s paintings=2C form the small m=
arble figure of a lyre-player from ancient Greece=2C from a Chinese three-=
footed bowl =E2=80=94 and into musical notes=2C words=2C ideas. In the who=
leheartedness of concentration=2C world
and self begin to cohere. With that state comes an enlarging: of what may=
 be known=2C what may be felt=2C what may be done.

Considering the unparalleled pleasures of practicing (https://www.brainpic=
kings.org/2015/01/07/glenn-kurtz-practicing/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) familiar to all who endeavor in the =E2=80=9Cabsorbing errand=
=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/14/an-absorbing-errand-ja=
nna-malamud-smith/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) of creative wor=
k=2C particularly to those who attain mastery (https://www.brainpickings.o=
rg/2014/01/22/daniel-goleman-focus-10000-hours-myth/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&m=
c_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Hirshfield points to deliberate practice as an esse=
ntial aspect of concentration =E2=80=94 one that transcends mechanical ski=
ll and reaches into the psychological=2C even the spiritual:

Violinists practicing scales and dancers repeating the same movements over=
 decades are not simply warming up or mechanically training their muscles.=
 They are learning how to attend unswervingly=2C moment by moment=2C to th=
emselves and their art; learning to come into steady presence=2C free from=
 the distractions of interest or boredom.

Illustration by Sydney Smith from The White Cat and the Monk (https://www.=
brainpickings.org/2016/04/11/the-white-cat-and-the-monk/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac719=
60&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C a 9th-century ode to the joy of uncompetitive p=
urposefulness

With an eye to the obsessive daily routines (https://www.brainpickings.org=
/2012/11/20/daily-routines-writers/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) and strange creative rituals (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/09/23/o=
dd-type-writers/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) of many writers=
=2C and to the state of intense focus in the creative act known as =E2=80=
=9Cflow=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/12/05/peter-turchi=
-a-muse-a-maze-book-flow/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) Hirshfie=
ld explores the path to concentration:

Immersion in art itself can be the place of entry=E2=80=A6 Yet however it=
 is brought into being=2C true concentration appears =E2=80=94 paradoxical=
ly =E2=80=94 at the moment willed effort drops away=E2=80=A6 At such momen=
ts=2C there may be some strong emotion present =E2=80=94 a feeling of joy=
=2C or even grief =E2=80=94 but as often=2C in deep concentration=2C the s=
elf disappears. We seem to fall utterly into the object of our attention=
=2C or else vanish into attentiveness itself.

This may explain why the creative is so often described as impersonal and=
 beyond self=2C as if inspiration were literally what its etymology implie=
s=2C something =E2=80=9Cbreathed in.=E2=80=9D We refer=2C however metaphor=
ically=2C to the Muse=2C and speak of profound artistic discovery and reve=
lation. And however much we may come to believe that =E2=80=9Cthe real=E2=
=80=9D is subjective and constructed=2C we sill feel art is a path not jus=
t to beauty=2C but to truth: if =E2=80=9Ctruth=E2=80=9D is a chosen narrat=
ive=2C then new stories=2C new aesthetics=2C are also new truths.

A century after Rilke extolled the soul-expanding power of difficulty (htt=
ps://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/10/rilke-letters-to-a-young-poet-sadnes=
s/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and urged us to =E2=80=9Carrang=
e our life according to that principle which counsels us that we must alwa=
ys hold to the difficult=2C=E2=80=9D Hirshfield writes:

Difficulty itself may be a path toward concentration =E2=80=94 expended ef=
fort weaves us into a task=2C and successful engagement=2C however laborio=
us=2C becomes also a labor of love. The work of writing brings replenishme=
nt even to the writer dealing with painful subjects or working out formal=
 problems=2C and there are times when suffering=E2=80=99s only open path i=
s through an immersion in what is. The eighteenth-century Urdu poet Ghalib=
 described the principle this way: =E2=80=9CFor the raindrop=2C joy is in=
 entering the river =E2=80=94 / Unbearable pain becomes its own cure.=E2=
=80=9D

Illustration by Andrea Dezs=C3=B6 for a special edition (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2015/07/20/best-brothers-grimm-illustrations/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac7=
1960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) of the original Brothers Grimm fairy tales

Echoing Nietzsche=E2=80=99s insistence that a full life requires embracing=
 rather than running from difficulty (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/1=
0/15/nietzsche-on-difficulty/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and=
 Alfred Kazin=E2=80=99s beautiful case for the reality-enlarging quality o=
f contradiction (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/20/alfred-kazin-jou=
rnals-perception-contradiction/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])=
 =2C Hirshfield adds:

Difficulty then=2C whether of life or of craft=2C is not a hindrance to an=
 artist. Sartre called genius =E2=80=9Cnot a gift=2C but the way a person=
 invents in desperate circumstances.=E2=80=9D Just as geological pressure=
 transforms ocean sediment into limestone=2C the pressure of an artist=E2=
=80=99s concentration goes into the making of any fully realized work. Muc=
h of beauty=2C both in art and in life=2C is a balancing of the lines of f=
orward-flowing desire with those of resistance =E2=80=94 a gnarled tree=2C=
 the flow of a statue=E2=80=99s draped cloth. Through such tensions=2C phy=
sical or mental=2C the world in which we exist becomes itself. Great art=
=2C we might say=2C is thought that has been concentrated in just this way=
: honed and shaped by a silky attention brought to bear on the recalcitran=
t matter of earth and of life. We seek in art the elusive intensity by whi=
ch it knows.

Hirshfield turns to the role of language in concentration and the role of=
 concentration in language=2C in writing=2C in poetry itself:

Great sweeps of thought=2C emotion=2C and perception are compressed to for=
ms the mind is able to hold =E2=80=94 into images=2C sentences=2C and stor=
ies that serve as entrance tokens to large and often slippery realms of be=
ing=E2=80=A6 Words hold fast in the mind=2C seeded with the surplus of bea=
uty and meaning that is concentration=E2=80=99s mark.

More than a century after William James asserted that =E2=80=9Ca purely di=
sembodied human emotion is a nonentity=E2=80=9D in his seminal theory of h=
ow our bodies affect our feelings (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/01/1=
1/what-is-an-emotion-william-james/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) =2C Hirshfield examines the dimensions of time and space in language thr=
ough the focusing lens of the body:

Shaped language is strangely immortal=2C living in a meadowy freshness out=
side of time.

But it also lives in the moment=2C in us. Emotion=2C intellect=2C and phys=
iology are inseparably connected in the links of a poem=E2=80=99s sound. I=
t is difficult to feel intimacy while shouting=2C to rage in a low whisper=
=2C to skip and weep at the same time.

Well before scientists came to study how repetition beguiles the brain (ht=
tps://www.brainpickings.org/2014/09/18/on-repeat-margulis/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac7=
1960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Hirshfield considers the enchantment of rhyth=
mic regularity. In a passage that calls to mind pioneering Harvard psychol=
ogist Jerome Bruner=E2=80=99s notion of =E2=80=9Ceffective surprise=E2=80=
=9D as the pillar of creativity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/04/21/=
jerome-bruner-on-knowing-left-hand-creativity/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C she describes the affective surprise at the heart of eve=
ry great work of art:

A regular returning in one dimension can bring unexpected turns in another=
: hunting a rhyme=2C the mind falls on a wholly surprising idea. This bala=
ncing between expected and unforeseen=2C both in aesthetic and cognitive s=
tructures=2C is near the center of every work of art. Through the gate of=
 concentration=2C defining yet open=2C both aspects enter.

Art by Maurice Sendak for The Big Green Book (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2015/06/04/the-big-green-book-robert-graves-maurice-sendak/?mc_cid=3Ded7=
ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Robert Graves

Hirshfield examines the role of rhetoric as a gatekeeper of concentration:

Before we can concentrate easily=2C we need to know where we stand. This i=
s the work of rhetoric=E2=80=A6 Traditionally defined as the art of choosi=
ng the words that will best convey the speaker=E2=80=99s intent=2C rhetori=
c=E2=80=99s concern is the precise and beautiful movement of mind in langu=
age.

In a sentiment of exceeding timeliness today =E2=80=94 one that calls to m=
ind Hannah Arendt=E2=80=99s masterwork on lying in politics (https://www.b=
rainpickings.org/2016/06/15/lying-in-politics-hannah-arendt/?mc_cid=3Ded7a=
c71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and Aldous Huxley=E2=80=99s lamentation of our=
 mistrust of sincerity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/28/aldous-hu=
xley-art-artists-sincerity-obvious/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) =E2=80=94 Hirshfield adds:

Americans distrust artful speech=2C believing that sincerity and deliberat=
ion cannot coexist=E2=80=A6 Romantic temperament =E2=80=A6 equates spontan=
eity and truth. But the word art is neighbor to artifice=2C and in human c=
ulture=2C as in the animal and vegetable worlds=2C desirability entails no=
t only the impulse of the moment but also enchantment=2C exaggeration=2C r=
earrangement=2C and deception. We don=E2=80=99t find the fragrance of nigh=
t-scented flowering tobacco or the display of a peacock=E2=80=99s tail ins=
incere =E2=80=94 by such ruses this world conducts its erotic business. To=
 acknowledge rhetoric=E2=80=99s presence in the beauty of poems=2C or any=
 other form of speech=2C is only to agree to what already is.

In another thought cast at poetry but ablaze with truth about all art and=
 about life itself=2C Hirshfield observes:

To be aware of a poem=E2=80=99s effects =E2=80=A6 requires only our alert=
 responsiveness=2C our presence to each shift in the currents of language=
 with an answering shift in our being=E2=80=A6 at a level closer to daydre=
am. But daydream with an added intensity: while writing=2C the mind moves=
 between consciousness and the unconscious in the effortless effort of con=
centration. The result=2C if the poet=E2=80=99s intensity of attention is=
 sufficient=2C will be a poem that brims with its own knowledge=2C water t=
rembling as if miraculously above the edge of a cup. Such a poem will be p=
erfect in the root sense of the word: =E2=80=9Cthoroughly done.=E2=80=9D

Daydreaming is indeed an apt analogy=2C for the making of poetry =E2=80=94=
 as=2C again=2C the making of all art =E2=80=94 radiates from a communion=
 of the conscious and the unconscious=2C a more wakeful counterpart to tha=
t =E2=80=9Csomething nameless=E2=80=9D which Mark Strand elegized in his s=
ublime ode to dreams (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/16/mark-strand=
-dreams-collected-poems/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Hirshfi=
eld captures this beautifully:

Making a poem is neither a wholly conscious activity nor an act of unconsc=
ious transcription =E2=80=94 it is a way for new thinking and feeling to c=
ome into existence=2C a way in which disparate modes of meaning and being=
 may join. This is why the process of revising a poem is no arbitrary tink=
ering=2C but a continued honing of the self at the deepest level.

Illustration by Lisbeth Zwerger for a special edition (https://www.brainpi=
ckings.org/2015/07/20/best-brothers-grimm-illustrations/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac719=
60&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) of the fairy tales of the Brothers Grimm

This dreamlike aspect comes most fully alive in one of poetry=E2=80=99s gr=
eat powers =E2=80=94 phanopoeia=2C the making of images. Hirshfield writes=
 of the poetic image:

The deepest of image=E2=80=99s meanings is its recognition of our continui=
ty with the rest of existence: within a good image=2C outer and subjective=
 worlds illuminate one another=2C break bread together=2C converse. In thi=
s way=2C image increases both vision and what is seen. Keeping one foot br=
aced in the physical and the other in the realm of inner experience=2C ima=
ge enlivens both.

But in bridging inner reality with the outer world=2C Hirshfield argues=2C=
 this halfway house of transcendence brings home something even larger=2C=
 even more monumental:

Poetry moves consciousness toward empathy.

Intelligence and receptivity are connected =E2=80=94 human meaning is made=
 by seeing what is=E2=80=A6 The outer world can be transformed by a subjec=
tively infused vision; inner event placed into the language of the physica=
l takes on an equally mysterious addition.

A powerful poetic image=2C Hirshfield suggests=2C both wrests truth out of=
 reality and confers truth upon it:

In a good image=2C something previously unformulated (in the most literal=
 sense) comes into the realm of the expressed. Without precisely this imag=
e=2C we feel=2C the world=E2=80=99s store of truth would be diminished; an=
d conversely=2C when a writer brings into language a new image that is ful=
ly right=2C what is knowable of existence expands.

[=E2=80=A6]

Thinking within the fields of image=2C the mind crosses also into the know=
ledge the unconscious holds =E2=80=94 into the shape-shifting wisdom of dr=
eam. Poetic concentration allows us to bring the dream-mind=E2=80=99s comp=
ression=2C displacement=2C wit=2C depth=2C and surprise into our waking mi=
nds. It is within dreamlife we first learn to read rain as grief=2C or the=
 may that a turtle=E2=80=99s walking may speak of containment and an awkwa=
rd=2C impeccable fortitude.

But the aspect of concentration perhaps most widely relevant beyond poetry=
 is that of narrative =E2=80=94 our supreme hedge against the entropy of e=
xistence. Hirshfield writes:

Storytelling=2C like rhetoric=2C pulls us in through the cognitive mind as=
 much as through the emotions. It answers both our curiosity and our longi=
ng for shapely forms: our profound desire to know what happens=2C and our=
 persistent hope that what happens will somehow make sense. Narrative inst=
ructs us in both these hungers and their satisfaction=2C teaching us to pe=
rceive and to relish the arc of moments and the arc of lives. If shapeline=
ss is an illusion=2C it is one we require =E2=80=94 it shields against arb=
itrariness and against chaos=E2=80=99s companion=2C despair. And story=2C=
 like all the forms of concentration=2C connects. It brings us to a deepen=
ed coherence with the world of others and also within the manny levels of=
 the self.

[=E2=80=A6]

Story remains a basic human path toward the discovery and ordering of mean=
ing and beauty.

Illustration by Dasha Tolstikova from The Jacket (https://www.brainpicking=
s.org/2014/11/12/the-jacket-kirsten-hall-dasha-tolstikova/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac7=
1960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) by Kirsten Hall=2C a sweet illustrated story abou=
t how we fall in love with books

Echoing Ursula K. Le Guin=E2=80=99s abiding wisdom on how imaginative stor=
ytelling expands our repertoire of possibilities (https://www.brainpicking=
s.org/2016/05/06/ursula-k-le-guin-freedom-oppression-storytelling/?mc_cid=
=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Hirshfield adds:

Story=2C at its best=2C becomes a canvas to which the reader as well as th=
e writer must bring the full range of memory=2C intellect=2C and imaginati=
ve response. The best stories are almost mythlike in their ability to supp=
ort alternative readings=2C different conclusions.

[=E2=80=A6]

Narrative carries the knowledge of our alteration through the shifting cur=
rents of circumstance and time.

Narrative=E2=80=99s essential counterpart is voice =E2=80=94 the waveform=
 of the soul in writing. Hirshfield writes:

A person=E2=80=99s heard voice is replete with information. So it is with=
 the voice of a poem.

[=E2=80=A6]

Voice =E2=80=A6 is the body language of a poem =E2=80=94 the part that can=
not help but reveal what it is. Everything that has gone into making us wh=
o we are is held there. Yet we also speak of writers =E2=80=9Cfinding thei=
r voice.=E2=80=9D The phrase is both meaningful and odd=2C a perennial puz=
zle: how can we =E2=80=9Cfind=E2=80=9D what we already use? The answer lie=
s=2C paradoxically=2C in the quality of listening that accompanies self-aw=
are speech: singers=2C to stay in tune=2C must hear not only the orchestra=
l music they sing with=2C but also themselves. Similarly=2C writers who ha=
ve =E2=80=9Cfound a voice=E2=80=9D are those whose ears turn at once inwar=
d and outward=2C both toward their own nature=2C thought patterns=2C and r=
hythms=2C and toward those of the culture at large.

In the essay=E2=80=99s closing passages=2C Hirshfield once again captures=
 a central truth about poetry that sets free a larger truth about life its=
elf =E2=80=94 about the limits of attention=2C about the relationship betw=
een what is known and what is knowable=2C about the nature of transformati=
on=2C about the perennial incompleteness of being. She writes:

No matter how carefully we read or how much attention we bring to bear=2C=
 a good poem can never be completely entered=2C completely known. If it is=
 the harvest of true concentration=2C it will know more than can be said i=
n any other way. And because it thinks by music and image=2C by story and=
 passion and voice=2C poetry can do what other forms of thinking cannot: a=
pproximate the actual flavor of life=2C in which subjective and objective=
 become one=2C in which conceptual mind and the inexpressible presence of=
 things become one.

Letting this wideness of being into ourselves=2C as readers or as writers=
=2C while staying close to the words themselves=2C we being to find in poe=
ms a way of entering both language and being on their own terms. Poetry le=
ads us into the self=2C but also away from it. Transparency is both capaci=
ous and focused. Free to turn inward and outward=2C free to remain still a=
nd wondering amid the mysteries of mind and world=2C we arrive=2C for a mo=
ment=2C at a kind of fullness that overspills into everything. One breath=
 taken completely; one poem=2C fully written=2C fully read =E2=80=94 in su=
ch a moment=2C anything can happen. The pressed oil of words can blaze up=
 into music=2C into image=2C into the heart and mind=E2=80=99s knowledge.=
 The lit and shadowed placed within us can be warmed.

Nine Gates: Entering the Mind of Poetry (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos=
/ASIN/0060929480/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) is a=
 small but immensely largehearted book=2C replete with radiant wisdom on t=
he creative act of composing a life=2C in poetry or in pulse. Complement i=
t with Hirshfield=E2=80=99s beautiful ode to the leap day (https://www.bra=
inpickings.org/2016/02/29/february-29-jane-hirshfield/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Mary Oliver on what attention really=
 means (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/01/20/mary-oliver-molly-malone-=
cook-our-world/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Elizabeth Alex=
ander on what poetry does for the human spirit (https://www.brainpickings.=
org/2015/07/29/elizabeth-alexander-ars-poetica-100-i-believe/?mc_cid=3Ded7=
ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and great writers=E2=80=99 collected wisdo=
m on the craft (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/05/03/advice-on-writing=
/?mc_cid=3Ded7ac71960&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .
