lation-mode: bicubic;border: 0;height: auto;line-height: 100%;outline: non=
e;text-decoration: none;padding: 5px 30px 10px 0px;display: inline;width:=
 50px!important;">Trust to the contradictions and see them <em>all</em>. N=
ever annul one force to give supremacy to another. The contradiction itsel=
f <em>is</em> the reality in all its manifoldness. Man from <em>his</em> v=
antage point can see reality only in contradictions. And the more faithful=
 he is to his perception of the contradiction=2C the more he is open to wh=
at there is for him to know. =E2=80=9CHarmony=E2=80=9D as an absolute good=
 is for the gods=2C not for man.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"-webkit-text-=
size-adjust: 100%;-ms-text-size-adjust: 100%;color: #262626;font-family: G=
eorgia=2C serif;font-size: 15px;line-height: 175%;text-align: left;">Cauti=
oning against chasing the myth of harmony =E2=80=94 a myth advanced=2C per=
haps most famously=2C by Emerson and woven into the fabric of modern cultu=
re in <a href=3D"http://brainpickings.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=3D=
13eb080d8a315477042e0d5b1&id=3D50c13bc4e9&e=3Da5eb5cdf67" style=3D"-webki=
